      <div class="faq-section" style="margin-top: 4rem;">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary);">What is a portfolio allocation calculator?</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">A portfolio allocation calculator is a financial tool that helps investors determine the ideal percentage of different asset classes, such as stocks, bonds, and cash, to hold in their investment portfolio based on their age, financial goals, and risk tolerance.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary);">How does the rule of 110 or 120 work for asset allocation?</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">The rule of 110 or 120 is a common rule of thumb for asset allocation. It suggests subtracting your age from 110 (or 120 for a more aggressive stance) to determine the percentage of your portfolio that should be invested in stocks. The remaining percentage is allocated to bonds and fixed-income assets.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary);">Why is asset allocation important?</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Asset allocation is critical because it fundamentally balances risk and reward in your investment portfolio. By diversifying across different asset classes, you reduce the overall volatility of your portfolio and ensure the risk level aligns with your investment timeline.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary);">How often should I rebalance my portfolio?</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">Experts generally recommend reviewing and potentially rebalancing your portfolio at least annually, or when your asset allocation drifts significantly (e.g., by 5% or more) from your target percentages. Major life events may also prompt a review.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem; background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem;">
          <h3 style="margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary);">What is the traditional 60/40 portfolio rule?</h3>
          <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">The 60/40 portfolio is a traditional investment strategy that allocates 60% of capital to equities (for growth) and 40% to bonds (for income and stability). It is designed to provide moderate growth while mitigating significant downside risk during market downturns.</p>
        </div>
